oFeiPd_aj5v8rHMcR4M7RIeYGovbJdWdAy71_Dn3XNITzvuKG-ARIeW7oWAiGea15JLzUQohVcd=
lI5pnWdE8XMV93zq-LbLJZc5k7M9FYElHpBmTj0u1f1azQXgZNepU71aip3OCaOYA7t0CvXt7ha=
JzBx3hyAGIIL3Fq5ph7HrRswpzWAuM_5xf_ZGFDw] than go through the process of se=
lling a home.=C2=A0=C2=A0
But unlike the millions of people who have had similarly rough experiences,=
 Rabois actually tried to start a company to fix the problem and bring liqu=
idity to the housing market. He went searching for $10 million for project =
=E2=80=9CHomerun,=E2=80=9D but was only able to secure $5 million. He reali=
zed that it had to be all or nothing, so he dropped it, but spent the bette=
r part of the next decade biding his time and trying to convince someone to=
 build it with him.=C2=A0
Then in 2010, Wu joined Y Combinator with his real estate startup and sough=
t Rabois out as an adviser. At their first meeting, Keith tried to convince=
 Eric to drop his idea, Movity, which provided location-based data to help =
home buyers make better decisions, and build Homerun with him. Wu turned hi=
m down and stuck with Movity (Rabois invested) and sold to Trulia in Decemb=
er 2010.
After two years at Trulia, Rabois tried to woo Wu again. This time, he succ=
eeded. A decade later, it was time to turn his idea into a reality.
In 2013, Wu built a landing page, opendoorrealty.co, to test whether people=
 would be willing to instantly sell their homes at a discount. Wu told the =
audience at NFX=E2=80=99s 2019 Proptech Summit [https://email.mg2.substack.=
com/c/eJxFULtuwzAQ-xprqyHJ70FDiyBr26Wrocc5ViNLhnyK4b-vnAwFDjiAxJFHaolwC_EQa=
9iQpA3iaI1gLe-rph6IEbVhfdMTu41TBFikdQJjArIm5ayWaIN_XlDKGzILNnHWcanqmna6ldC3=
E9VDbzrZsmlSkpw-o0zGgtcg4AHxCB6IEzPiuhXVe8GvefZ9L4-QMCkodVhORKKei-r6KKqLe3v=
7vHz_hI8vTazglFM6cMZ4U1NesvKR5iA7k3V_i5ouN15uSW0o9f3UIlH4gCpE62-Zvs9yAfckcq=
Yx7yV5i8cIXioH5hUXXwU9v8djBeFh3xwgQnyBZwf9ULesJdnMhNyU__f5AzSZevo] that he =
discovered that there is =E2=80=9Ca significant liquidity premium for a cer=
tain set of sellers.=E2=80=9D He talked to ten sellers, and asked whether t=
hey would be willing to sell their home for 88 cents on the dollar. Some sa=
id yes, and for those who didn=E2=80=99t, he worked his way up until he fou=
nd an equilibrium. Assessing the opportunity based on price elasticity of t=
he demand curves is in the company=E2=80=99s DNA, and that=E2=80=99s really=
 important. We=E2=80=99ll come back to why a little later.=C2=A0
Rabois, then a partner at Khosla Ventures, committed to lead a $10 million =
Series A for the renamed Opendoor, with Wu at the helm as CEO. At the time,=
 $10 million was a big first check, but both men understood that they could=
n=E2=80=99t MVP their way into transforming residential real estate. They n=
eeded to do it right from the beginning. Part of doing it right meant recru=
iting a founding team with necessary experience:=C2=A0
Ian Wong, CTO: Stanford Ph.D. dropout and Square Data Scientist
JD Ross, VP Product: VP, Product at Addepar
Ryan Johnson, VP Operations (founding team): Bain Capital and McKinsey
In its founding team, Opendoor had the real estate, pricing, product, and c=
apital markets expertise necessary to make housing liquid.
Sticking to the Plan
With the team in place, Opendoor closed its Series A, led by Khosla, in Jul=
y 2014. Incredibly, its Series A deck [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJx=
FkM1ugzAQhJ8GH5HtYH4OPkRq0x6qqmql5oiMvYATY1NjoOTpa5JDpV2tNLOrTztSBOic3_jopo=
DmCXytFSc5LQ8sq5DimSIlK5Ge6tYDDEIbHvwMaJwbo6UI2tn7BcaUoZ6zvGhwLMCFkkV5kIIoR=
piQbQatyFu0c2oxKw1WAocF_OYsIMP7EMYpORwTeoqlvF4g7ZzrDKTSDVFqtYHdiU1Ot8_f_O2r=
Oq8vH-3t9fL0fi6a4_dz_bMu4khY3Fk0rEhziinGFSWEsgzTlKTL3DtRqAi9JBkeOppOczMFIa8=
7B3luXWic17aL9rUXA5i7ER-u4xxmq8NWgxWNAfXIIjzSu78WthG4hXUyEAL4h7gHVFZZTnIUYc=
rFGO0_5w9Nh4Sb] laid out most of the plan that Opendoor is still executing =
on today.=C2=A0
Here=E2=80=99s how it works:=C2=A0
Opendoor uses an Automated Valuation Model (AVM) to algorithmically price h=
omes.
Sellers enter their address, answer some questions, and receive an offer in=
stantly.=C2=A0
Opendoor sends an inspector to confirm the condition and price repairs (and=
 collect data to feed back into the model), before settling on a final pric=
e.=C2=A0
Opendoor charges 6% in the form of a discount to cover fees plus a liquidit=
y discount of between 0-6% depending on riskiness. Its average today is 7.3=
% total (6% + 1.3%).
Opendoor closes with the seller quickly, makes repairs, and sells the home.=
 Originally, it did this through agent partners, and increasingly, it=E2=80=
=99s bringing that process in-house.
Rabois and Wu started the company on the belief that certain customers woul=
d be willing to pay a premium for certainty, and that many more customers w=
ould take certainty for free. Simply put, the strategy that Opendoor has pu=
rsued since day one is:=C2=A0
Start with the least price sensitive customers =E2=86=92 use them to improv=
e accuracy and lower costs =E2=86=92 attract slightly more price sensitive =
customers =E2=86=92 use them to improve accuracy and lower costs =E2=86=92 =
launch new markets with least price sensitive customers =E2=86=92 rinse, wa=
sh, repeat
This is the first point at which Opendoor starts to remind you of Amazon. I=
n Two Ways to Predict the Future [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVkMFu=
hSAQRb9GdhpAsbhg0U1_w4CMT_oUDAzP-PfladKmyUwmmZuZk3snjfAI8VR7SEhygjg6q1jPZSu=
6gVjVWSaFJC6NcwTYtFsVxgxkz2Z1k0YX_HVBKRdkUb1h89Aa2YOQtKWWU9YLJow1ndSgZ_LmjD=
pbB34CBS-IZ_BAVrUg7qlqPyv-VcoHNCE6_2hSNgn19GymsBVhL41HqA99phpDvUewbsIaF6jnj=
DkCcYpTTunAGeOio7xhzSsvQX_YQvquOro9-L-3JKpfXpGfi95gvYTicixzy97hOYLXZgV7B4B3=
ZJcfPHdQHo60AiLEe_lORQ5dz3pSYDaU7Pwf5wcTwILg], I wrote that Jeff Bezos had =
a strong claim for the G.W.O.A.T. (Greatest Worldbuilder of All Time) crown=
 because he saw that everything would be sold online in the future and set =
out to patiently execute on his long-term vision. While Bezos started with =
books, which the internet with its infinite shelf space was uniquely positi=
oned to handle, Rabois and Wu started with homes, which the internet has be=
en notoriously bad at handling.=C2=A0
As Byrne Hobart pointed out [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVUMuOwyAM_=
JpyawQUUnLg0Mv-RsTDadgSiMB0lb9f2h5WKxnZjGWPZ5xBuOdy6D1XJK1CmYPXbOTqIsVEvBae=
KalIqPNSADYTosbSgOzNxuAMhpzeE5RySVZNhV2EZUrAdJWOScutMgsdlfNGioWRF89smg-QHGh=
4QjlyAhL1irjX0-V24l89fFiWoTZb0bjH4PLWsb2_vEPyOZdzgdrvcNh60T8mnjvQxZCgOeWUTp=
wxLgXlAxuebc3m6jvP90nQ7c7_bSZFp4w2l5Duvf1YzQbx3ega5563lgIeMyRjI_iPfPwY9laDx=
w46wU-NgAjlA748UZMY2Ug6mc_dufTH8wta9IKE], =E2=80=9CHomes may be the single =
most heterogeneous asset class and product in existence. There are 95m sing=
le-family homes in the US, all of which are in some way unique.=E2=80=9D So=
 Rabois and Wu picked the most homogenous product within the universe of US=
 residential real estate: newly constructed homes in Phoenix.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s important to keep in mind how systematic Opendoor has been thr=
oughout its life. The Series A deck highlighted three risks -- model accura=
cy, buying overvalued homes, and capital -- and used its Series A and Phoen=
ix to address each. It used subsequent rounds to de-risk, scale, expand, ac=
quire, and drive down costs. Remove friction, improve margins.=C2=A0
For a full history, including links to fundraising articles, check out this=
 Google doc [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEtvgzAMxz8NuQ0lITA45NCtq=
6ZJPVZ7XFAgBrKShOWxim-_UA6TbNnyQ3_714sAo3UrX6wPKHpwrZKcVLQuStYgyZkkdVkj5dvB=
AWihZh5cBLTEbla9CMqa-wbGtEQTr-qK0g4PHa2rhlWNKIjoGkwLygYy1AXadFoRpQLTA4dfcKs=
1gGY-hbD4rDhk9JRM2t7no7XjDHlv9V6JGkzY0uSkuLz9fF2Gj3mBQ9u9P8eS6dtL-xD0uXwSry=
1M54PUn0web2kcpApZcYp-yYqjn4RTZkSKU0wxbightGSY5iT_jZMVjzKd9J0xrEea-9j5IPrrd=
gZy3NjQ2W07ta-T0DDfGwlHm6KORoW1BSO6GeROKuxs74-HdQFu4OZnCAHcXtzw1QkWqVASkzZB=
Nv86f_y5jfs].
By the time it raised its last venture round in March 2019, less than five =
years since it raised its Series A, Opendoor accomplished a lot:=C2=A0
Raised $1.48 billion in equity capital and over $2 billion in debt capacity
Launched in twenty-one markets
Acquired Open Listings and OS National to expand its service offering
Improved pricing, brought down costs, accessed cheaper capital
Purchased and sold billions of dollars worth of homes ($1.7 billion in 2018=
 [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUMuOwyAM_Jpy2wgIZJMDh172NyIeTsOWQASm=
Uf5-aXNYyRpbY9mjGasRHimfak8FSS2QZ-8UG_jYSzERp4RjoxyJL_OSATbtg8JcgezVBG81-hQ=
_F5RySVbVCy2WkcueLdIJyyYKAzNi1MZNktt213RmXZ2HaEHBC_KZIpCgVsS93Pr7jf-0Oo6j2_=
wT3N7ZtDVCZ_Q2QGkjp2xqjYo38Abe1BPyV4Y9ZSReccopnThjXArKO9a96pr0t2tCvzdBtwfvS=
jUFtX2-v5OsYkKTso-Ptn6ueoPwWTSTc-tbjR7PGaI2AdzlH6_EPnbw3EFFOEoARMgX-Q5lnMTA=
BtLEXGrRxX-dP1wff5I])
Hit a $3.8 billion valuation
In 2019 alone, Opendoor did $4.7 billion in revenue with positive contribut=
ion margins. All of that capital, including SoftBank money, which has often=
 been a kiss of death for its recipients, made Opendoor stronger. Opendoor=
=E2=80=99s strategy had always involved launching markets, proving and impr=
oving the model, de-risking, and launching new markets. Whereas SoftBank mo=
ney forced companies like Wag to expand before they were ready, Opendoor kn=
ew exactly when it was ready to expand and what it wanted to accomplish by =
doing so. Its focus on unit economics meant that it wouldn=E2=80=99t light =
the money on fire, and a strong balance sheet meant that it was ready for t=
urbulence.=C2=A0
When the Coronavirus hit, Opendoor was prepared. It dramatically de-risked,=
 laying off [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE2OwyAMhU9TdkSEQn4WLGYz1=
4gIOA3TBEdgOsrth7SLkSxbepb9nj5nCR6YTnNgJlYypCl403ZyuGs1Mm-Ubwc9sJCnJQHsNmyG=
UgF2lHkLzlLA-L4QQmq2GiUH0Mous9BedFL0urc9tEM3ei3c2LPLZ7LFB4gODLwgnRiBbWYlOvL=
t_nWT37UI3OpSiW5tHO5VkEKKOoSqrdW1ZVxotvHJZ-ue4DkeED1i4qvN3MaI9bjKlu825_ACvt=
kTl4W7QhTig981x4UHyhz2Y8MTINevLJjLSYyybaVWQjZt8yor2t7XmD83JfaHbHKZM1XbKxtLJ=
iLNmOrTun6udoftvaiIpjr3EgOdE0Q7b-A_9OjD-w2DzgNMhN-8ARGkj3ghHUbVtR2rZh4r-Pjv=
8wfkjZXX] over 600 employees (35% of staff), paused buying while continuing=
 to sell, and brought its home inventory down from $1 billion to $172 milli=
on. CFO Carrie Wheeler pointed out that it sold down without sacrificing ma=
rgins, which dipped just slightly from 7.1% in Q1 to 6.8% in Q2.=C2=A0
Then in the midst of the pandemic, some good news. Last week, after a week =
of rumors, Chamath [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUMuOwyAM_JpyjMAhWX=
LgsJf9jYiH07BNIALTKn-_pD2sZMmyR-OZsTOE95RPfaRCrBbMc_BajKD6QU7Ma-mFGhQLZV4y4=
m7CpilXZEe1W3CGQopvBucwsFUr2Ts1Dry33oJbrJdgFjWJ3o0LIDh26cym-oDRocYn5jNFZJte=
iY5y679v8NOKXoEIc-fS3ia3mt3QyoIGDpxPIAQMkkMnumddk_ny7cbvTfL9Dl2ptpBxj4vLso6=
JbMoh3hv8aHdwewPN_9z6XmOgc8Zo7Ib-E40-z3g7pfNAHfFVNrz8fJZXXjXJUYysifnUvhL_df=
4AnUV1GA] announced that his second SPAC, IPOB, was merging with Opendoor t=
o go public at a $4.8 billion valuation.=C2=A0
Chamath=E2=80=99s SPACtacular Vision
Chamath is the voice of the SPAC movement, and CNBC is his pulpit. Last Tue=
sday, he went on CNBC to lay out his thesis for Opendoor:=C2=A0
Residential real estate is a massive market ($1.6 trillion annually) with l=
ow customer satisfaction and an inconsistent experience (28% of realtors do=
 the job part time). Opendoor=E2=80=99s model has five tailwinds at its bac=
k:
Underbuilding since the financial crisis has led to a supply/demand imbalan=
ce
Rising state taxes and elimination of SALT deductions are motivating people=
 to move
75 million millennials entering the housing market who expect to transact o=
nline
WFH is here to stay, so people are moving to higher quality-of-life cities
The Fed signaled that it will keep interest rates near zero at least throug=
h 2023
The former Facebook exec and Social Capital CEO has high hopes for the comp=
any:=C2=A0=C2=A0
The times I=E2=80=99ve come on, I=E2=80=99ve tried to find asymmetric upsid=
e opportunities and present them to you. This to me feels like Bitcoin in 2=
012, Amazon in 2015, Tesla in 2016, Virgin last year. This is an enormous b=
et for me, and I think that Opendoor is going to build a huge, huge busines=
s.
After a run-up to $18, IPOB closed the week at $14.60. A healthy run-up, bu=
t nothing like high-margin tech IPOs like Snowflake [https://email.mg2.subs=
tack.com/c/eJxFkE2OhCAQhU_T7DBAS6sLFrOZaxh-ypZRwUDRE28_qItJCFV5FXivPqsR3jEd=
ao8ZScmQRu8Uf4n-KduBONU63sue-DxOCWDTflWYCpC9mNVbjT6G6wVjQpJZsU72vAXnBIDpeAf=
dIAfrpJQdwJO15PQZdXEeggUFH0hHDEBWNSPu-fH8eojvejadFsDcmJJ9gFyv7B2kxsatTgP85l=
oyRrtcTYi_06oXoJdE9-Rt7aNOmd4_UUza-fCmDkxBaso0ASL1e6SCCUYHypmoUWVf1_Dq1NggO=
BeyZaLhzafMUXeuRv15tGx7iyYXk1Hb5YxEkgoRTUzVoY6XWW-wXoOKaax1K8HjMULQZgV3E8Sb=
-QUEjx3UudVaU0G6xRNrP7Qv_iLVzMUKP_z7_AGhmZie], which more than doubled on i=
ts first day of trading.=C2=A0
That makes sense, though. With both SPACs and IPOs on the table as viable o=
ptions, IPOs are for easily-understood companies, and SPACs are for compani=
es whose potential is underappreciated. Opendoor is underappreciated.
