px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Homes are emotional.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1=
a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Puja and I a=
re having our first kid, a son, in less than a month. We spent this Saturda=
y cleaning up my parents&#8217; house and getting rid of old junk that we h=
adn&#8217;t used for years to make space for all of the new stuff the littl=
e guy will need whenever we come visit. As with any cleaning project, we st=
arted by emptying one closet and decided to throw out twenty-plus years&#82=
17; worth of trash and memories from around the house. As we emptied closet=
s we hadn&#8217;t opened in years, my mom came up with reasons we should ke=
ep that old empty picture frame or half-used can of WD-40, told us that we =
should just dry clean the sleeping bag we bought in 1998 in case we might w=
ant to use it at some point in the future. None of it is rational, but it&#=
8217;s not unique either. Mari Kondo has made a fortune convincing people t=
o let go of things that once held importance but no longer do.&nbsp;</p><p =
style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1e=
m 0;">And that&#8217;s just the <em>stuff</em>. You would have to pry us ou=
t of the house itself.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px=
; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Maybe that&#8217;s why housing is =
one of the last major categories that technology has left alone. Sure, comp=
anies have tried. Tons of them. The startup graveyard is filled with compan=
ies led by entrepreneurs who realized that the way we buy and sell homes su=
cks, but couldn&#8217;t ultimately figure out how to change it. They weren&=
#8217;t thinking big or long-term enough. The companies that have made the =
biggest impact, like <a href=3D"https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUEGOhC=
AQfM1wNIDg4IHDXvYbBqUd2UEw0IxxX7-oh0066aQq1VVdk0F4xXToLWYkJUManNWs46qVoidWC=
